## HyperStation | Mission Control – Feature Report

### Overview

HyperStation is a real-time **mission control dashboard** for the HyperCode multi‑agent swarm. It gives you a single place to **see**, **steer**, and **approve** everything your agents are doing, with a neurodivergent‑friendly, low‑stress UI that emphasizes visibility and control. [skywork](https://skywork.ai/blog/agent/mission-control-for-ai-agents-managing-multiple-agents-in-github/)

***

### Core Objectives

- Provide live visibility into all active agents and tasks (no more “black box” AI). [verdent](https://www.verdent.ai/guides/ralph-tui-ai-agent-dashboard)
- Enable human‑in‑the‑loop approvals for risky actions before any code or data is changed. [aufaitux](https://www.aufaitux.com/blog/agentic-ai-design-patterns-enterprise-guide/)
- Reduce cognitive load with a clean, chunked layout that surfaces only the most important signals by default (status, commands, approvals, results). [mission-control-prompts.vercel](https://mission-control-prompts.vercel.app)

***

### Key Features

#### 1. Live Agent Status Grid

- Shows each agent (Database Architect, Backend Specialist, Frontend Specialist, Coder Agent, etc.) with:
  - Current state: Idle, Working, Waiting for Approval, Error.
  - Role/description so you always know “who” is doing what.
- Auto‑refresh / polling every few seconds so the view stays current without manual reloads. [nexastack](https://www.nexastack.ai/blog/multi-agent-ai-infrastructure)

**Benefit:** Matches modern “mission control” patterns where you can glance at the board and immediately see which parts of the system are active or stuck. [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Hs_jDO0M1I)

***

#### 2. Command Console (Task Launcher)

- Text input for natural language commands like:
  - `build a TODO app with database, API, and React frontend`
  - `run: build a spaceship UI`
- Sends structured `POST /execute` requests to the `crew-orchestrator` behind the scenes.
- Newly submitted commands immediately appear in the task history with a status like Queued → Running → Completed. [skywork](https://skywork.ai/blog/agent/mission-control-for-ai-agents-managing-multiple-agents-in-github/)

**Benefit:** Acts like an “agent command center” where you can launch complex multi‑agent workflows from a single place, similar to emerging mission control UIs for AI workforces. [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sP-SQEE7K-Y)

***

#### 3. Real-Time Approval Modal (Human-in-the-Loop)

- WebSocket connection to `/ws/approvals` listens for approval requests from the orchestrator in real time. [docs.cloud.google](https://docs.cloud.google.com/architecture/choose-design-pattern-agentic-ai-system)
- When an agent proposes an action (e.g., “create migration”, “modify files”, “deploy to staging”), HyperStation:
  - Pops a high‑visibility **“AUTHORIZATION REQUIRED”** modal.
  - Shows: agent name, action description, risk level, and key details.
  - Provides **Authorize** and **Abort** buttons, posting the decision back to the orchestrator (e.g., `/approvals/respond`). [aufaitux](https://www.aufaitux.com/blog/agentic-ai-design-patterns-enterprise-guide/)
- Handles reconnection and `ws://` vs `wss://` so it works both locally and via tunnels/hosting. [aufaitux](https://www.aufaitux.com/blog/agentic-ai-design-patterns-enterprise-guide/)

**Benefit:** Aligns with best‑practice guidance that agentic systems must expose a clear **control plane**, with explicit approvals and auditability before high‑impact actions are taken. [verdent](https://www.verdent.ai/guides/ralph-tui-ai-agent-dashboard)

***

#### 4. Task History & Activity Feed

- Shows a chronological list of tasks:
  - Command text
  - Involved agents
  - Final status (Completed, Failed, Timed Out, Aborted)
  - Timestamps
- Mirrors patterns used in other mission control dashboards where users can quickly replay what happened overnight or during long‑running agent sessions. [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Hs_jDO0M1I)

**Benefit:** Acts as an audit trail and a learning tool—great for debugging, demos, and showing “what the swarm actually did while I was away.” [jontsai](https://www.jontsai.com/2026/02/12/building-mission-control-for-my-ai-workforce-introducing-openclaw-command-center)

***

#### 5. Live Logs Panel

- Streams orchestration events from the `crew-orchestrator` (e.g., `task_received`, `rag_query`, `agent_started`, `approval_requested`, `approval_received`, `task_completed`).  
- Inspired by real-world multi‑agent observability tools, where visibility into each step is considered essential for safe deployment. [nexastack](https://www.nexastack.ai/blog/multi-agent-ai-infrastructure)

**Benefit:** You can match what you see in the UI (agent state, approvals) with the underlying events, which is critical for trust and production debugging. [verdent](https://www.verdent.ai/guides/ralph-tui-ai-agent-dashboard)

***

#### 6. Connection & System Status

- Header includes:
  - **Connection indicator** (Connected / Offline) based on API/WebSocket reachability.
  - **Live clock** implemented client‑side to avoid hydration issues but still signal “this is live, not a static screenshot.”
- Follows modern mission‑control UI patterns where a persistent status bar summarizes connectivity and recency at a glance. [mission-control-prompts.vercel](https://mission-control-prompts.vercel.app)

**Benefit:** Immediate reassurance that the dashboard is talking to the orchestrator and that what you’re seeing is “now”, not stale. [skywork](https://skywork.ai/blog/agent/mission-control-for-ai-agents-managing-multiple-agents-in-github/)

