### UX & Neurodivergent-Friendly Design

HyperStation is particularly tuned for neurodivergent users:

- **Chunked layout**: Separate, clearly-labelled zones for agents, commands, logs, and approvals, minimizing context switching. [mission-control-prompts.vercel](https://mission-control-prompts.vercel.app)
- **Low-surprise interactions**: Agents never execute high‑risk actions without an explicit approval popup; nothing happens “behind your back”. [verdent](https://www.verdent.ai/guides/ralph-tui-ai-agent-dashboard)
- **Progressive disclosure**: High‑level summaries up front, detailed logs and metadata available when you want them, echoing enterprise design guidance for agent dashboards. [mission-control-prompts.vercel](https://mission-control-prompts.vercel.app)
- **Consistent feedback**: Every action (command sent, approval clicked) has a visible effect in either status, history, or logs, reducing ambiguity and anxiety. [youtube](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Hs_jDO0M1I)

This matches emerging best practices for **human-centered agentic UX**, where transparency, reversibility, and control are non‑negotiable. [agentic-design](https://agentic-design.ai/patterns/multi-agent)

***

### Architecture & Integration

- **Backend**: `crew-orchestrator` exposes:
  - `GET /agents` for agent status.
  - `GET /tasks` for task history.
  - `GET /logs` for streaming events.
  - `POST /execute` for new tasks.
  - WebSocket `/ws/approvals` for approval requests.
- **Frontend**:
  - `lib/api.ts` wraps these endpoints.
  - `page.tsx` wires live polling + WebSocket + UI.
  - `ApprovalModal.tsx` encapsulates the approval UX.
  - `Clock.tsx` provides client‑only, hydration-safe time display.

This mirrors the “central orchestrator + mission control dashboard” pattern described in modern multi‑agent infrastructure guides and enterprise design patterns. [docs.cloud.google](https://docs.cloud.google.com/architecture/choose-design-pattern-agentic-ai-system)

